{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5dece21a-101f-4fc5-9cc8-f16e0fa8a7c5","content":"The project doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but here's the standard configuration. Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`dotnet run`** builds and launches your project automatically.\n- For a **published build**, replace with `\"command\": \"path/to/MyMcpServer\"` (no `args`).\n- If your server needs environment variables, add an `\"env\": {}` block.\n\nAfter saving, open the **MCP server panel** in VS Code (Command Palette → `MCP: List Servers`) to verify it starts correctly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b509c5f4-032c-4c52-8c57-c791282a3bd0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist. The user is asking a general \"how to configure\" question. I can answer this from knowledge. Let me give them the configuration for a C# MCP server using stdio transport (the most common pattern).","outputTokens":322},"id":"f6d17db2-da56-40a9-8c5c-4676f3eccc42","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:04:17.332Z","parentId":"177c4e24-3744-49ca-a0c9-bbbd81400cc9"}
